, "y0": 4.92, "x1": 39.83, "y1": 7.11}, {"x0": 45.61, "y0": 0.89, "x1": 53.74, "y1": 6.95}, {"x0": 61.37, "y0": 2.04, "x1": 68.04, "y1": 6.76}, {"x0": 10.42, "y0": 9.15, "x1": 54.4, "y1": 10.4}, {"x0": 9.1, "y0": 7.11, "x1": 14.6, "y1": 11.0}, {"x0": 53.87, "y0": 37.31, "x1": 90.7, "y1": 56.65}, {"x0": 12.09, "y0": 67.34, "x1": 44.04, "y1": 85.55}, {"x0": 53.54, "y0": 67.25, "x1": 86.28, "y1": 87.1}], "full_text": "Radiology\nNon traumatic chest emergency\nWhile the majority of patients have underlying cardiovascular aetiologies, but a\nsubset of patients have underlying non-cardiovascular conditions although they\npresent with similar symptoms of chest pain, dyspnoea, cough, hemoptysis and\nhaematemesis.\nThoracic emergencies are mainly diagnosed and differentiated through:\n1. Clinical history\n2. Physical examination\n3. Electrocardiography\n4. Laboratory investigations\n5. Imaging: when specific diagnosis remains elusive imaging plays an important\nrole in the assessment of patients with cardiac and non-cardiac chest conditions.\nAcute pulmonary embolism\n• Acute PE is associated with high\nmorbidity and mortality, particularly in\nthe acute care setting.\n• the patient presented with sudden-\nonset chest pain. CT Pulmonary\nAngiography demonstrates emboli in\nright main pulmonary artery (arrow).\nAortic dissection and aneurysm\n• Any mechanism that weakens the media of the aorta may result in aortic dilatation\nand aneurysm formation and, eventually, intramural hemorrhage, aortic\ndissection, or rupture.\n• The patient can present with sudden severe chest pain.\nMassively aneurysmal aorta displacing the\nCTA: The true lumen (more dense)\ntrachea to the right. Consolidation in the left\nThe false lumen (less dense).\nlower lobe. Small adjacent left pleural\neffusion.\n76"}